    "image_with_text_t6KzFw": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_CcwiLn": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Maria Struk transforms molten glass into objects that toe the line between design and delight. Since launching <a href=\"https://www.mariaidadesigns.com/\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Maria Ida Designs</span></a> in 2015, the Vancouver-based glass artist has been creating functional, unpretentious <a href=\"https://www.mariaidadesigns.com/shop-x4py2\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">hand-blown objects</span></a> that bring warmth and personality into everyday spaces. </p><p>We visited Maria in her showroom above <a href=\"https://terminalcityglass.com/\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Terminal City Glass Co-op,</span></a> where she brings glass to life in the hot shop. Perfect copies of candy-bright pieces share shelf space with delightfully wobbly experiments. Here, it’s easy to see how curiosity, patience, and a love of colour shape every object she makes. </p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_CcwiLn"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/IMG_6351.jpg",
        "height": "adapt",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
        "layout": "image_first",
        "desktop_content_position": "middle",
        "desktop_content_alignment": "left",
        "content_layout": "no-overlap",
        "color_scheme": "background-1",
        "mobile_content_alignment": "left",
        "padding_top": 36,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_wKVLmh": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_CLbqn8": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Q: </strong>What 3 words would your family/friends use to describe you? </p><p><strong>A: </strong>Curious, thoughtful, and independent. </p><p><strong>Q:</strong> Do you remember the very first piece you made?</p><p><strong>A:</strong>  It was a very small paperweight. I thought it was the most amazing thing ever, even though it was just a blob<em> [laughs]. </em>My mom still has the first paperweight I ever made, it’s pretty cute. </p><p><strong>Q: </strong>What advice would you give to your younger self just starting out in the hot shop?</p><p><strong>A:</strong> I would remind myself that nothing needs to be perfect right away. It’s a learning process, and it takes time to get good at glassblowing. I would be easier on myself, and be kind to myself.</p><p></p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_CLbqn8"
